<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>Homework 05</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <alert>Instructions:</alert> Complete all the exercises below and submit your work via 
      <url href="https://www.gradescope.com/courses/1238540">Gradescope</url> by Monday March 2 at 10pm.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <page>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write two or more paragraphs describing the <alert>best</alert> ways to get stuck and unstuck on 
          a math problem.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f,g\colon \mathbb R^n\to \mathbb R</m> be two continuous maps. Suppose there is a number <m>N</m> 
          such that <m>\lVert x\rVert \gt N</m> implies <m>g(x)\le 0</m> and <m>f(x)\ge 1</m>. Prove that the subspaces
          <md>
            \{x\in \mathbb R^n\mid f(x)=g(x)\}\quad\text{and}\quad \{x\in \mathbb R^n\mid f(x)\le g(x)\}
          </md>
          are compact.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For <m>X</m> a space, the <term>cone</term> on <m>X</m> is
          <md>
            CX := ([0,1]\times X)/{\sim}
          </md>
          where <m>(s,x)\sim (t,y)</m> means <m>(s,x)=(t,y)</m> or <m>s=t=0</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Draw a picture of <m>CS^1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that the map <m>f\colon CS^n\to D^{n+1}</m> given by <m>[(t,x)]\mapsto tx</m> is well-defined and continuous.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the Fundamental Theorem of Topology to prove that <m>f\colon CS^n\to D^{n+1}</m> is a homeomorphism.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>n\gt 0</m>. Prove that there is a homeomorphism <m>D^n/{\sim}\cong S^n</m> where <m>x\sim y</m> means 
          <m>x=y</m> or <m>x,y\in S^{n-1}\subseteq D^n</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Prove that
          <md>
            <mrow>s\colon [0,\infty) \amp \longrightarrow \mathbb R</mrow>
            <mrow>t \amp \longmapsto (t-\lfloor t\rfloor)^{\lceil t\rceil}+\lfloor t\rfloor</mrow>
          </md>
          is continuous. Here <m>\lfloor~\rfloor</m> and <m>\lceil~\rceil</m> are the <term>floor</term> and <term>ceiling</term> 
          functions, respectively. (Instead of proving this statement directly, you might enjoy developing a lemma about when 
          piecewise defined functions are continuous, and then applying that lemma in this case.)
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>
